  "text": "## Kafka Consumer API Migration Analysis\n\nThe analysis reveals a modern Kafka consumer architecture where the old ConsumerConnector API has been completely replaced. The current codebase contains two primary consumer implementations accessible through a delegation pattern.\n\n### New KafkaConsumer API Architecture (apache/kafka)\n\nThe **Consumer interface** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/Consumer.java) defines the contract for all consumer implementations. **KafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java) is the primary public implementation that delegates to either **ClassicKafkaConsumer** or **AsyncKafkaConsumer** based on configuration, using the **ConsumerDelegateCreator** pattern.\n\n**ClassicKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ClassicKafkaConsumer.java) provides backward compatibility with the classic group protocol (pre-KIP 848). This is the synchronous consumer implementation where all network I/O happens in the application thread. It implements the **ConsumerDelegate** interface, which extends Consumer to expose internal methods for testing.\n\n**AsyncKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AsyncKafkaConsumer.java) represents the new asynchronous consumer using the newer group protocol (post-KIP 848).\n\n### Offset Management in New API\n\nOffset management in the new KafkaConsumer API uses the **OffsetAndMetadata** class (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/OffsetAndMetadata.java), which encapsulates the offset position along with optional metadata and leader epoch information. This represents a significant evolution from the old ConsumerConnector approach.\n\nThe **CommitRequestManager** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CommitRequestManager.java) handles offset commit operations. Key behavioral differences from the legacy API include:\n1. Support for leader epochs to detect log truncation\n2. Asynchronous and synchronous commit callbacks with guaranteed ordering\n3. OffsetAndMetadata objects containing rich metadata including leader epoch\n4. Automatic commit configuration via ConsumerConfig properties\n\nThe **OffsetFetcher** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/OffsetFetcher.java) manages offset validation and reset operations, including automatic offset reset strategies and leader epoch validation.\n\nThe **SubscriptionState** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/SubscriptionState.java) class tracks topic subscriptions, partition assignments, and consumer positions for all assigned partitions, maintaining thread-safe state management.\n\n### Camel Kafka Component Integration\n\nApache Camel integrates with the new KafkaConsumer API through its **KafkaConsumer** component (components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/KafkaConsumer.java), which is a Camel-specific consumer endpoint, not the Kafka consumer itself.\n\nCamel's offset management is abstracted through the **AbstractCommitManager** interface (components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/consumer/AbstractCommitManager.java), which provides multiple implementations:\n- **SyncCommitManager** for synchronous offset commits using KafkaConsumer.commitSync()\n- **AsyncCommitManager** for asynchronous offset commits\n- **CommitManagers factory** (components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/consumer/CommitManagers.java) for creating appropriate managers\n\nCamel's AbstractCommitManager.forceCommit() method wraps KafkaConsumer.commitSync() with OffsetAndMetadata, showing the migration pattern where offset+1 is committed to represent the next record to consume.\n\n### Key Behavioral Differences\n\n1. **Offset Representation**: The new API uses OffsetAndMetadata objects instead of simple long offsets, including leader epoch tracking for truncation detection\n2. **Commit Callbacks**: The new API provides OffsetCommitCallback with guaranteed ordering of async commits before subsequent sync operations\n3. **Auto-Commit**: Configured through ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG and AUTO_COMMIT_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG properties\n4. **Position Tracking**: Uses FetchPosition with OffsetAndMetadata in SubscriptionState for thread-safe tracking\n5. **Backward Compatibility**: ClassicKafkaConsumer maintains compatibility with classic group protocol while AsyncKafkaConsumer uses the newer protocol\n6. **Leader Epoch Support**: New API tracks leader epochs for robustness against log truncation scenarios\n\nThe migration from the old ConsumerConnector API to KafkaConsumer represents a shift from complex, protocol-specific implementations to a more unified, feature-rich consumer API with better offset management, truncation detection, and group protocol flexibility."
}

